'''Kushida Shrine''' (くしだじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Imizu|Q851411|qid=Q851411|1=Imizu}}, {{ill|lt=Toyama Prefecture|Q132929|qid=Q132929|1=Toyama Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}, and its former {{ill|lt=shrine rank|Q10444029|qid=Q10444029|1=Shakaku}} was {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=kensha|1=Ken-sha|qid=Q90139226}}.

It is worshiped as a deity of marital harmony, family harmony, and matchmaking.

=== Enshrined deities ===
With {{ill|lt=Susanoo|Q272993|qid=Q272993|lt=Take-Susanoo-no-Mikoto|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto}} and {{ill|qid=Q505469|lt=Kushinadahime|Q505469|qid=Q505469|qid=Q505469|lt=Kushinadahime-no-Mikoto|1=Kushinadahime}} as main {{ill|lt=enshrined deities|Q11591100|qid=Q11591100|1=Saijin}}, the following historical figures are additionally enshrined.
* Minister Takeuchi ({{ill|lt=Takeuchi no Sukune|Q1073668|qid=Q1073668|1=Takenouchi no Sukune}})
* Minister Toyotomi ({{ill|lt=Toyotomi Hideyoshi|Q187550|qid=Q187550|1=Toyotomi Hideyoshi}})
* Lord Minamoto no Yoshiaki ({{ill|lt=Shiba Yoshimasa|Q11500863|qid=Q11500863|1=Shiba Yoshiyuki}})
* Great Arieke ({{ill|lt=Maeda Toshiie|Q1196817|qid=Q1196817|1=Maeda Toshiie}})
Also, due to {{ill|lt=shrine mergers|Q11590700|qid=Q11590700|1=Shrine Consolidation Policy}} of nearby shrines in the Meiji period, the following deities are worshiped as well.
* {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Amaterasu-kōdaijin|1=UNKNOWN}}
* {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Sukunahikona-no-Mikoto|1=Sukunabikona|qid=Q3275687}}
* {{ill|UNKNOWN|qid=Q2329261|lt=Toyotama-hime-no-Mikoto|1=Toyotama-hime}}
* Sokotsutsu-no-o-no-Mikoto ({{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Sumiyoshi deity|1=UNKNOWN}})
* Okinaga-tarahime-no-Mikoto and Hondawake-no-Mikoto ({{ill|lt=Hachiman deity|Q261637|qid=Q261637|1=Hachiman}})
* {{ill|lt=Tenjin faith|Q66890725|qid=Q66890725|lt=Tenman Tenjin|1=Tenjin faith}} ({{ill|lt=Sugawara no Michizane|Q382005|qid=Q382005|1=Sugawara no Michizane}})

However, the 'Old shrine records and similar in Etchū Province' records the deity as Ōwakago-no-Mikoto. Ōwakago-no-Mikoto is another name of Ōhatahushi-no-Ōkami, main deity of {{ill|lt=Kushida Shrine (Fukuoka)|Q865839|qid=Q865839|lt=Kushida Shrine|1=Kushida Shrine}} in Chikuzen Province.

=== History ===
Shrine tradition says it was founded by invitation from Takeuchi no Sukune in the age of {{ill|lt=Emperor Chūai|Q179971|qid=Q179971|1=Emperor Chūai}}.

A local legend says a giant serpent lived in a large nearby pond and ate villagers. One time, when it ate a girl, the comb in her hair lodged in its throat and it died; worship of the girl and the comb is said to have begun this shrine.

It is listed as "Kushida Shrine, Imizu District, Etchū Province" in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}.

=== Festivals ===
At the autumn annual festival, the {{ill|lt=fire-walking|Q929202|qid=Q929202|1=Firewalking}} rite is famous.

=== Other ===
Because stained-glass artist {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ōtomo Fumiya|1=UNKNOWN}} from Imizu had deep attachment to this shrine in life, amulets embroidered with stained-glass motifs are produced. In the precincts, the "Ōtomo Fumiya Stained Glass Memorial Hall" (single-story reinforced concrete, about 90 m<sup>2</sup>, free admission) opened on {{ill|lt=December 2|Q2296|qid=Q2296|1=December 2}} {{ill|lt=2007|Q2024|qid=Q2024|1=2007}}<ref>From Kita Nippon Shimbun, morning edition December 3, 2007, p.26: "Pioneer stained-glass works gathered at Daimon Kushida Shrine, Ōtomo Fumiya opens, 80 works stored and exhibited in sequence."</ref>. In summer {{ill|lt=2016|Q25245|qid=Q25245|1=2016}}, a lantern with stained glass was completed in front of the memorial hall<ref>[https://www.hokurikushinkansen-navi.jp/pc/news/article.php?id=NEWS0000009297 Stained-glass patterned amulets for first shrine visit: Imizu Kushida Shrine] (Hokuriku-Shinetsu Tourism Navi, 2016-12-27)</ref>.

In December 2019, to commemorate the enthronement of {{ill|lt=Naruhito|Q217096|qid=Q217096|lt=the current emperor|1=Naruhito}}, a new shinmon gate (height 3.6 m, width 5.2 m, depth 3.2 m) was constructed. Stained-glass lanterns were also installed beside it<ref>From Kita Nippon Shimbun, morning edition December 22, 2019, p.20: "Kushida Shrine builds new shinmon to celebrate emperor's enthronement; stained-glass lanterns also installed."</ref>.

=== Transportation ===
* Parking: available
* Take {{ill|lt=Imizu City Community Bus|Q11458552|qid=Q11458552|1=Imizu City Community Bus}}, get off at "Matsubara Kominkan-mae," immediately nearby.

